    {
      "id": "intro",
      "type": "theory",
      "title": "Your four big A1 wins",
      "body": "# Review A1\n\nYou have learned the four most important A1 building blocks. Here they come together one more time, compactly — and this time combined inside a single sentence.\n\n| Topic | Core rule | Example |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Gender** | -o → masculine (el), -a → feminine (la) | el libro, la casa |\n| **ser / estar** | Could it change? No → ser, Yes → estar | Soy alta / Estoy feliz |\n| **Present** | -AR/-ER/-IR: hablo, como, vivo | Hablo español. |\n| **Preterite** | regular takes the accent (hablé, habló), irregular drops it (fui, hice) | Ayer hablé. |\n\nNo new vocabulary — just consolidation and combination."
    },
    {
      "id": "step-watchouts",
      "type": "theory",
      "title": "The classic traps",
      "body": "## What to watch out for\n\n- **ser vs. estar**: *Soy estudiante* (identity → ser), but *Estoy cansado* (state → estar). The question is always: \"Could this change?\"\n- **The accent decides the tense**: *hablo* = I speak (present), *hablé* = I spoke (preterite). A single accent flips the meaning completely.\n- **Regular vs. irregular in the preterite**: regular forms carry the accent (hablé, habló, comí); the common irregular forms carry NONE (fui, hice, tuve).\n- **The contractions al and del**: *a + el = al*, *de + el = del*. So *Voy al mercado*, *Vengo del mercado* — never *a el* or *de el*."
    },
